As usual, we have the deep-dive Coffee Lake coverage in our Core i7-8700K Review: Coffee Lake Brews A Great Gaming CPU review, but for those of you without the time to sift through all 13 pages, we've condensed all of our gaming results to give you a cheat sheet of sorts on Intel's new halo product.
Coffee Lake has arrived, and after nearly a decade of quad-core doldrums in Intel's mainstream desktop space, the company finally decided to bulk up its Core i7, i5, and i3 series. Intel added two more cores to each of the families and also increased the Turbo Boost frequencies to the highest an Intel chip has seen. Better yet, those increased resources come with a minimal price increase over the Kaby Lake models for the unlocked K-series chips, and the same price for the locked models. We can thank AMD for that.
We also have articles that compare Intel's full Coffee Lake lineup to Kaby Lake and a full breakdown of comparisons to AMD's beefy Ryzen stable.
And No, Coffee Lake will not run in Z270 motherboards.
So, if you whip out your wallet for Intel's six-core, 12-thread flagship and a new motherboard, what does that give you on the gaming front?

This. Our 99th percentile FPS chart provides a geometric mean of the results, converted into an FPS measurement, of all the games in our test suite. That single figure boils the story down pretty nicely, although we've also provided the performance results in each game so you can see how the Core i7-8700K fares in your favorite titles.
Despite a few missteps, the Core i7-8700K lives up to Intel’s claims. Although it doesn't beat the -7700K by a massive margin, the Coffee Lake flagship does deliver better performance in stock and overclocked form. AMD's Ryzen processors still offer competitive pricing and solid gaming performance, but Coffee Lake's gaming performance widens the gap considerably.
Intel's additional cores speed up performance in threaded tasks, which will also be a boon for the streaming crowd, but the faster Turbo Boost (up to 4.7 GHz) maintains the company's advantage in single threaded titles, albeit with a few cases of a slight step back from the Kaby Lake processors.
Image1
Image2
Image3
Image4 Image1
Image2
Image3
Image4
But bleeding edge performance is only part of the equation. We demand good value--a point AMD drove home with its speedy Ryzen lineup. Intel has obviously taken note, and the additional cores comes without radical price increases. Overall, the Core i7-8700K represents a solid value for those who demand the ultimate in performance, and the lesser Core i5 and i3 SKUs also look promising for the more pragmatic among us.
The Core i7-8700K is simple to overclock and won't require exotic cooling solutions unless you're chasing the bleeding edge, which makes it a fun chip for enthusiasts.
Altogether, the Core i7-8700K is the nimblest gaming chip we've tested, and it also offers surprising performance in our full suite of application tests. As we noted in the review:
Intel has its 10nm Cannon Lake processors coming in the second half of 2018, and AMD has a Ryzen refresh cycle coming next year. Knowing this, should you upgrade now or wait for the next wave of hardware? Due to the iterative nature of most updates, we rarely recommend jumping forward one, or even two generations. However, if you routinely find yourself running productivity workloads that might be served well by Core i7-8700K's extra cores, we could see replacing a quad-core chip with six cores. Gamers interested in maximum performance or streaming also stand to benefit, though in a world of single-GPU graphics configurations, you'd be hard-pressed to bottleneck an overclocked -7700K with even a GeForce GTX 1080 Ti (particularly at the high resolutions it's meant to drive).
The Core i7-8700K took home our Editor's Choice award. So feel free to take a dip in Coffee Lake if you've got the dosh--we doubt you'll be disappointed. We're working on testing the i5 and i3 models now, so stay tuned.

...them. In a recent interview, Teigen revealed that she has embraced her body’s changes throughout her pregnancies, emphasizing the importance of self-acceptance. “I’ve learned to love my stretch marks as a part of my journey,” she said. 

Teigen also shared her skincare routine, which includes moisturizing regularly with oils and creams specifically designed for pregnant women. “I use a combination of coconut oil and a rich body butter to keep my skin hydrated,” she explained. 

While she acknowledges that genetics play a significant role in whether or not someone develops stretch marks, Teigen encourages others to focus on the beauty of their bodies rather than the imperfections. “Every mark tells a story,” she added. 

Her candidness about body image has resonated with many, inspiring a broader conversation about the realities of pregnancy and the importance of loving oneself through all stages of life.

...Oceanside Beach when he noticed a commotion in the water. A swimmer had been caught in a rip current and was struggling to stay afloat. Without hesitation, Wilson sprang into action, diving into the turbulent waves. He swam against the current, reaching the distressed swimmer just in time. With his training and experience, he was able to secure the individual and guide them back to safety.

The swimmer, a local resident, expressed immense gratitude for Wilson's quick response and bravery. "I truly believe he saved my life," the swimmer said during the ceremony where Wilson was recognized. The Oceanside Lifeguard Association presented Wilson with a commendation plaque, highlighting his dedication and courage. "This is what we train for," Wilson stated humbly, downplaying his heroics. "I’m just glad I was there when it mattered." The community celebrated Wilson's actions, reinforcing the importance of lifeguards in ensuring beach safety.

The squad features a mix of promising young talent and experienced players, all eager to showcase their skills on a larger stage. Coach Jamie Thompson expressed his excitement about the upcoming carnival, emphasizing the importance of teamwork and development. "This is a fantastic opportunity for these young athletes to gain valuable experience and demonstrate their potential," Thompson said. 

Among the standout selections are several players who have excelled in local competitions, including standout forward Liam Carter and dynamic midfielder Sarah Jenkins. The team will undergo a rigorous training regimen leading up to the carnival, focusing on both physical conditioning and tactical strategies. 

The Great Southern Colts Carnival is expected to attract scouts from various leagues, providing players with a chance to catch the eye of potential recruiters. The squad will be finalized closer to the event, with Thompson keen to ensure that the best possible team represents the Great Southern region.

The host, who was discussing various topics, inadvertently mentioned "he" when referring to the baby, prompting a surprised reaction from the audience. After realizing her slip, she quickly attempted to redirect the conversation, but the moment had already captured the attention of viewers.

Social media erupted with speculation, as fans took to platforms to express their joy and anticipation for the new arrival. Many shared their theories about potential names and even offered parenting advice, showcasing the strong connection her audience feels with her.

While the star has yet to officially confirm the gender of her baby, insiders suggest that she is over the moon with the news. As she prepares for motherhood, fans are eagerly awaiting more updates, hoping for a glimpse into her journey as she navigates this exciting new chapter in her life.

Overall, the Core i7-8700K represents a solid value for those who demand the ultimate in performance, and the lesser Core i5 and i3 SKUs also look promising for the more pragmatic among us.
The Core i7-8700K is simple to overclock and won't require exotic cooling solutions unless you're chasing the bleeding edge, which makes it a fun chip for enthusiasts.
Altogether, the Core i7-8700K is the nimblest gaming chip we've tested, and it also offers surprising performance in our full suite of application tests. As we noted in the review:
Intel has its 10nm Cannon Lake processors coming in the second half of 2018, and AMD has a Ryzen refresh cycle coming next year. Knowing this, should you upgrade now or wait for the next wave of hardware? Due to the iterative nature of most updates, we rarely recommend jumping forward one, or even two generations. However, if you routinely find yourself running productivity workloads that might be served well by Core i7-8700K's extra cores, we could see replacing a quad-core chip with six cores. Gamers interested in maximum performance or streaming also stand to benefit, though in a world of single-GPU graphics configurations, you'd be hard-pressed to bottleneck an overclocked -7700K with even a GeForce GTX 1080 Ti (particularly at the high resolutions it's meant to drive).
The Core i7-8700K took home our Editor's Choice award. So feel free to take a dip in Coffee Lake if you've got the dosh--we doubt you'll be disappointed. We're working on testing the i5 and i3 models now, so stay tuned.

the prestigious BAFTA Awards. The couple arrived in style, with the Duchess dazzling in a custom-made gown that shimmered under the venue's grand chandeliers. As they mingled with A-list celebrities, the atmosphere buzzed with excitement and anticipation for the evening's accolades.

But bleeding edge performance is only part of the equation. We demand good value--a point AMD drove home with its speedy Ryzen lineup. Intel has obviously taken note, and the additional cores comes without radical price increases. Overall, the Core i7-8700K represents a solid value for those who demand the ultimate in performance, and the lesser Core i5 and i3 SKUs also look promising for the more pragmatic among us.
The Core i7-8700K is simple to overclock and won't require exotic cooling solutions unless you're chasing the bleeding edge, which makes it a fun chip for enthusiasts.
Altogether, the Core i7-8700K is the nimblest gaming chip we've tested, and it also offers surprising performance in our full suite of application tests. As we noted in the review:
Intel has its 10nm Cannon Lake processors coming in the second half of 2018, and AMD has a Ryzen refresh cycle coming next year. Knowing this, should you upgrade now or wait for the next wave of hardware? Due to the iterative nature of most updates, we rarely recommend jumping forward one, or even two generations. However, if you routinely find yourself running productivity workloads that might be served well by Core i7-8700K's extra cores, we could see replacing a quad-core chip with six cores. Gamers interested in maximum performance or streaming also stand to benefit, though in a world of single-GPU graphics configurations, you'd be hard-pressed to bottleneck an overclocked -7700K with even a GeForce GTX 1080 Ti (particularly at the high resolutions it's meant to drive).
The Core i7-8700K took home our Editor's Choice award. So feel free to take a dip in Coffee Lake if you've got the dosh--we doubt you'll be disappointed. We're working on testing the i5 and i3 models now, so stay tuned.

...as the country navigates a complex recovery from the pandemic. The official Purchasing Managers' Index (PMI) rose to 52.0 in May, up from 51.4 in April, indicating robust expansion as any reading above 50 signifies growth. Analysts had anticipated a more modest increase, reflecting a surge in demand both domestically and internationally.

The data suggests that government stimulus measures and a rebound in global trade are beginning to take effect, bolstering confidence among manufacturers. New orders surged, with export orders also showing signs of improvement, driven by a recovery in key markets.

However, challenges remain, including rising raw material costs and supply chain disruptions. Economists warn that while the manufacturing sector shows resilience, the broader economy still faces uncertainties, particularly in consumer spending and the services sector, which has been slower to recover. Policymakers are expected to monitor these trends closely as they consider future economic strategies.

This. Our 99th percentile FPS chart provides a geometric mean of the results, converted into an FPS measurement, of all the games in our test suite. That single figure boils the story down pretty nicely, although we've also provided the performance results in each game so you can see how the Core i7-8700K fares in your favorite titles.
Despite a few missteps, the Core i7-8700K lives up to Intel’s claims. Although it doesn't beat the -7700K by a massive margin, the Coffee Lake flagship does deliver better performance in stock and overclocked form. AMD's Ryzen processors still offer competitive pricing and solid gaming performance, but Coffee Lake's gaming performance widens the gap considerably.
Intel's additional cores speed up performance in threaded tasks, which will also be a boon for the streaming crowd, but the faster Turbo Boost (up to 4.7 GHz) maintains the company's advantage in single threaded titles, albeit with a few cases of a slight step back from the Kaby Lake processors.

But bleeding edge performance is only part of the equation. We demand good value--a point AMD drove home with its speedy Ryzen lineup. Intel has obviously taken note, and the additional cores comes without radical price increases. Overall, the Core i7-8700K represents a solid value for those who demand the ultimate in performance, and the lesser Core i5 and i3 SKUs also look promising for the more pragmatic among us.
The Core i7-8700K is simple to overclock and won't require exotic cooling solutions unless you're chasing the bleeding edge, which makes it a fun chip for enthusiasts.
Altogether, the Core i7-8700K is the nimblest gaming chip we've tested, and it also offers surprising performance in our full suite of application tests. As we noted in the review:
Intel has its 10nm Cannon Lake processors coming in the second half of 2018, and AMD has a Ryzen refresh cycle coming next year. Knowing this, should you upgrade now or wait for the next wave of hardware? Due to the iterative nature of most updates, we rarely recommend jumping forward one, or even two generations. However, if you routinely find yourself running productivity workloads that might be served well by Core i7-8700K's extra cores, we could see replacing a quad-core chip with six cores. Gamers interested in maximum performance or streaming also stand to benefit, though in a world of single-GPU graphics configurations, you'd be hard-pressed to bottleneck an overclocked -7700K with even a GeForce GTX 1080 Ti (particularly at the high resolutions it's meant to drive).
The Core i7-8700K took home our Editor's Choice award. So feel free to take a dip in Coffee Lake if you've got the dosh--we doubt you'll be disappointed. We're working on testing the i5 and i3 models now, so stay tuned.

...Petronas has announced plans to expand its operations in Southeast Asia, focusing on renewable energy and sustainable practices. The state-owned oil and gas company aims to diversify its portfolio amid the global shift towards cleaner energy sources. 

In a statement released on Monday, Petronas outlined its commitment to invest in solar and wind energy projects, as well as carbon capture technologies. The company is also exploring partnerships with local firms to enhance its capabilities in the region.

"Transitioning to a low-carbon future is not just a necessity but an opportunity for growth," said Petronas CEO Tengku Muhammad Taufik. "We are dedicated to playing a pivotal role in the energy transition while ensuring energy security for the communities we serve."

This strategic move comes as governments across Southeast Asia ramp up efforts to meet climate goals, with many countries setting ambitious targets for reducing carbon emissions in the coming decades.

The Lodgepole Complex fire, which began in late July, has been particularly challenging due to its rapid spread fueled by strong winds and dry vegetation. Local communities have rallied together, providing support to those displaced by the fires and assisting in recovery efforts. 

State officials are urging residents to remain vigilant and adhere to fire restrictions, as the potential for new fires continues. The Montana Department of Natural Resources and Conservation is assessing the damage and coordinating resources for affected areas, while also emphasizing the importance of preparedness for future fire seasons. As the summer draws to a close, the focus shifts to recovery and rebuilding for those impacted by this devastating wildfire season.

As usual, we have the deep-dive Coffee Lake coverage in our Core i7-8700K Review: Coffee Lake Brews A Great Gaming CPU review, but for those of you without the time to sift through all 13 pages, we've condensed all of our gaming results to give you a cheat sheet of sorts on Intel's new halo product.
Coffee Lake has arrived, and after nearly a decade of quad-core doldrums in Intel's mainstream desktop space, the company finally decided to bulk up its Core i7, i5, and i3 series. Intel added two more cores to each of the families and also increased the Turbo Boost frequencies to the highest an Intel chip has seen. Better yet, those increased resources come with a minimal price increase over the Kaby Lake models for the unlocked K-series chips, and the same price for the locked models. We can thank AMD for that.
We also have articles that compare Intel's full Coffee Lake lineup to Kaby Lake and a full breakdown of comparisons to AMD's beefy Ryzen stable.
And No, Coffee Lake will not run in Z270 motherboards.
So, if you whip out your wallet for Intel's six-core, 12-thread flagship and a new motherboard, what does that give you on the gaming front?

This. Our 99th percentile FPS chart provides a geometric mean of the results, converted into an FPS measurement, of all the games in our test suite. That single figure boils the story down pretty nicely, although we've also provided the performance results in each game so you can see how the Core i7-8700K fares in your favorite titles.
Despite a few missteps, the Core i7-8700K lives up to Intel’s claims. Although it doesn't beat the -7700K by a massive margin, the Coffee Lake flagship does deliver better performance in stock and overclocked form. AMD's Ryzen processors still offer competitive pricing and solid gaming performance, but Coffee Lake's gaming performance widens the gap considerably.
Intel's additional cores speed up performance in threaded tasks, which will also be a boon for the streaming crowd, but the faster Turbo Boost (up to 4.7 GHz) maintains the company's advantage in single threaded titles, albeit with a few cases of a slight step back from the Kaby Lake processors.

Image3
Image4
But bleeding edge performance is only part of the equation. We demand good value--a point AMD drove home with its speedy Ryzen lineup. Intel has obviously taken note, and the additional cores comes without radical price increases. Overall, the Core i7-8700K represents a solid value for those who demand the ultimate in performance, and the lesser Core i5 and i3 SKUs also look promising for the more pragmatic among us.
The Core i7-8700K is simple to overclock and won't require exotic cooling solutions unless you're chasing the bleeding edge, which makes it a fun chip for enthusiasts.
Altogether, the Core i7-8700K is the nimblest gaming chip we've tested, and it also offers surprising performance in our full suite of application tests. As we noted in the review:
Intel has its 10nm Cannon Lake processors coming in the second half of 2018, and AMD has a Ryzen refresh cycle coming next year. Knowing this, should you upgrade now or wait for the next wave of hardware? Due to the iterative nature of most updates, we rarely recommend jumping forward one, or even two generations. However, if you routinely find yourself running productivity workloads that might be served well by Core i7-8700K's extra cores, we could see replacing a quad-core chip with six cores. Gamers interested in maximum performance or streaming also stand to benefit, though in a world of single-GPU graphics configurations, you'd be hard-pressed to bottleneck an overclocked -7700K with even a GeForce GTX 1080 Ti (particularly at the high resolutions it's meant to drive).
The Core i7-8700K took home our Editor's Choice award. So feel free to take a dip in Coffee Lake if you've got the dosh--we doubt you'll be disappointed. We're working on testing the i5 and i3 models now, so stay tuned.

...year, according to a report from the Office for National Statistics. The findings highlight a growing concern over the safety and well-being of older adults, particularly those living alone or in care facilities. Experts warn that neglect can take many forms, including emotional abuse, financial exploitation, and physical harm.

Charities and advocacy groups are calling for increased awareness and action from families and communities to protect vulnerable seniors. They emphasize the importance of regular check-ins, open communication, and fostering supportive environments to help prevent isolation and abuse. 

Additionally, the report suggests that local authorities should enhance training for caregivers and improve monitoring systems to identify signs of neglect early. With the aging population on the rise, it is crucial for society to prioritize the safety and dignity of elderly individuals, ensuring they receive the care and respect they deserve.

...was not only getting her hair cut for the first time but also had to do so in front of a live audience. As part of a local charity event aimed at raising awareness for mental health, she volunteered to have her transformation streamed online. The teen, who has struggled with anxiety and self-image issues, decided to face her fears head-on.

With a supportive crowd cheering her on, she sat in the salon chair, her heart racing. The hairdresser, known for her gentle approach, reassured her throughout the process. As the scissors snipped away, the teen began to feel a sense of empowerment. Each lock of hair that fell to the floor symbolized a step toward overcoming her insecurities.

By the end of the event, not only did she leave with a fresh new look, but she also inspired many viewers to embrace their own challenges and seek help when needed.

As usual, we have the deep-dive Coffee Lake coverage in our Core i7-8700K Review: Coffee Lake Brews A Great Gaming CPU review, but for those of you without the time to sift through all 13 pages, we've condensed all of our gaming results to give you a cheat sheet of sorts on Intel's new halo product.
Coffee Lake has arrived, and after nearly a decade of quad-core doldrums in Intel's mainstream desktop space, the company finally decided to bulk up its Core i7, i5, and i3 series. Intel added two more cores to each of the families and also increased the Turbo Boost frequencies to the highest an Intel chip has seen. Better yet, those increased resources come with a minimal price increase over the Kaby Lake models for the unlocked K-series chips, and the same price for the locked models. We can thank AMD for that.
We also have articles that compare Intel's full Coffee Lake lineup to Kaby Lake and a full breakdown of comparisons to AMD's beefy Ryzen stable.
And No, Coffee Lake will not run in Z270 motherboards.
So, if you whip out your wallet for Intel's six-core, 12-thread flagship and a new motherboard, what does that give you on the gaming front?

That single figure boils the story down pretty nicely, although we've also provided the performance results in each game so you can see how the Core i7-8700K fares in your favorite titles.
Despite a few missteps, the Core i7-8700K lives up to Intel’s claims. Although it doesn't beat the -7700K by a massive margin, the Coffee Lake flagship does deliver better performance in stock and overclocked form. AMD's Ryzen processors still offer competitive pricing and solid gaming performance, but Coffee Lake's gaming performance widens the gap considerably.
Intel's additional cores speed up performance in threaded tasks, which will also be a boon for the streaming crowd, but the faster Turbo Boost (up to 4.7 GHz) maintains the company's advantage in single threaded titles, albeit with a few cases of a slight step back from the Kaby Lake processors.

Overall, the Core i7-8700K represents a solid value for those who demand the ultimate in performance, and the lesser Core i5 and i3 SKUs also look promising for the more pragmatic among us.
The Core i7-8700K is simple to overclock and won't require exotic cooling solutions unless you're chasing the bleeding edge, which makes it a fun chip for enthusiasts.
Altogether, the Core i7-8700K is the nimblest gaming chip we've tested, and it also offers surprising performance in our full suite of application tests. As we noted in the review:
Intel has its 10nm Cannon Lake processors coming in the second half of 2018, and AMD has a Ryzen refresh cycle coming next year. Knowing this, should you upgrade now or wait for the next wave of hardware? Due to the iterative nature of most updates, we rarely recommend jumping forward one, or even two generations. However, if you routinely find yourself running productivity workloads that might be served well by Core i7-8700K's extra cores, we could see replacing a quad-core chip with six cores. Gamers interested in maximum performance or streaming also stand to benefit, though in a world of single-GPU graphics configurations, you'd be hard-pressed to bottleneck an overclocked -7700K with even a GeForce GTX 1080 Ti (particularly at the high resolutions it's meant to drive).
The Core i7-8700K took home our Editor's Choice award. So feel free to take a dip in Coffee Lake if you've got the dosh--we doubt you'll be disappointed. We're working on testing the i5 and i3 models now, so stay tuned.

...Vettel, who started from pole position, faced intense pressure from Bottas in the closing stages of the race. The Finnish driver, who had been gaining ground after a late pit stop, pushed hard to close the gap, but Vettel's experience and skill behind the wheel proved decisive. 

As the two cars raced side by side through the final corners, the tension in the air was palpable. Vettel managed to hold his line, expertly navigating the tricky turns while Bottas looked for any opportunity to overtake. In a nail-biting finish, the German crossed the line just 0.6 seconds ahead of Bottas, securing his first victory of the season and giving Ferrari a much-needed boost in the championship standings.

Post-race, Vettel expressed his relief and joy, stating, "It was a tough battle, but we kept our cool and executed our strategy perfectly." The win marked a significant moment for Ferrari, reigniting hopes for a competitive season ahead.

California lawmakers have reintroduced a bill aimed at achieving 100-percent carbon-free energy by 2045, reigniting discussions on the state's ambitious climate goals. The legislation, which had previously faced hurdles, seeks to accelerate the transition from fossil fuels to renewable energy sources, including solar, wind, and hydroelectric power. Proponents argue that this move is essential for combating climate change and ensuring a sustainable future for the state.

The bill outlines a comprehensive framework for increasing renewable energy production while phasing out reliance on natural gas and other carbon-emitting sources. Supporters, including environmental groups and clean energy advocates, emphasize the economic benefits of green jobs and the potential for California to lead the nation in climate policy. However, critics express concerns about the feasibility of such a rapid transition and the potential impact on energy prices. As the legislative session progresses, the bill's fate remains uncertain, but it reflects California's ongoing commitment to environmental leadership.

Intel has its 10nm Cannon Lake processors coming in the second half of 2018, and AMD has a Ryzen refresh cycle coming next year. Knowing this, should you upgrade now or wait for the next wave of hardware? Due to the iterative nature of most updates, we rarely recommend jumping forward one, or even two generations. However, if you routinely find yourself running productivity workloads that might be served well by Core i7-8700K's extra cores, we could see replacing a quad-core chip with six cores. Gamers interested in maximum performance or streaming also stand to benefit, though in a world of single-GPU graphics configurations, you'd be hard-pressed to bottleneck an overclocked -7700K with even a GeForce GTX 1080 Ti (particularly at the high resolutions it's meant to drive).
The Core i7-8700K took home our Editor's Choice award. So feel free to take a dip in Coffee Lake if you've got the dosh--we doubt you'll be disappointed. We're working on testing the i5 and i3 models now, so stay tuned.

the region, experts say. With India as a member, the SCO has gained a more diverse perspective on security and economic issues, particularly in relation to counter-terrorism and regional connectivity. Analysts believe that India's participation can enhance cooperation among member states, particularly in areas such as trade, energy security, and cultural exchanges.

India's strategic interests align with the SCO's goals, especially in combating extremism and fostering economic development in Central Asia. The country’s involvement is expected to facilitate greater collaboration on infrastructure projects, which are crucial for enhancing trade routes and connectivity across the region.

Moreover, India's membership is seen as a counterbalance to China's growing influence within the organization. As New Delhi navigates its complex relationships with both Beijing and Islamabad, its role in the SCO could be pivotal in shaping the future dynamics of regional geopolitics. The upcoming summit is anticipated to further solidify these objectives and enhance multilateral ties among member nations.

...Commission (CQC) following an inspection. The CQC highlighted several areas of concern, including response times and the need for better management of resources. Inspectors noted that while some staff provided compassionate care, there were inconsistencies in service delivery that affected patient outcomes.

The report pointed out that the trust struggled to meet national response time targets, particularly for emergency calls. Patients reported long waits for ambulances, which raised concerns about their safety and well-being. The Chief Inspector emphasized the importance of addressing these issues promptly to ensure that patients receive timely and effective care.

In response, the East of England Ambulance Service NHS Trust acknowledged the findings and committed to implementing a comprehensive improvement plan. This plan will focus on enhancing training for staff, optimizing resource allocation, and improving communication with patients. The trust aims to achieve a higher rating in future inspections and restore public confidence in its services.

...defeat, a troubling trend that has left fans and players alike searching for answers. The Rangers, who had high hopes for a deep playoff run, struggled to find their rhythm at Madison Square Garden, where they had previously thrived during the regular season. 

Despite a strong start to the game, with an early goal from their captain, the team faltered as the Canadiens capitalized on defensive lapses. The crowd, once electric, grew increasingly frustrated as the Rangers failed to convert on power plays and missed key opportunities to shift momentum. 

Coach Gerard Gallant expressed disappointment in the team's inability to perform at home, emphasizing the need for a mental reset before their next game. As usual, we have the deep-dive Coffee Lake coverage in our Core i7-8700K Review: Coffee Lake Brews A Great Gaming CPU review, but for those of you without the time to sift through all 13 pages, we've condensed all of our gaming results to give you a cheat sheet of sorts on Intel's new halo product.
Coffee Lake has arrived, and after nearly a decade of quad-core doldrums in Intel's mainstream desktop space, the company finally decided to bulk up its Core i7, i5, and i3 series. Intel added two more cores to each of the families and also increased the Turbo Boost frequencies to the highest an Intel chip has seen. Better yet, those increased resources come with a minimal price increase over the Kaby Lake models for the unlocked K-series chips, and the same price for the locked models. We can thank AMD for that.
We also have articles that compare Intel's full Coffee Lake lineup to Kaby Lake and a full breakdown of comparisons to AMD's beefy Ryzen stable.
And No, Coffee Lake will not run in Z270 motherboards.
So, if you whip out your wallet for Intel's six-core, 12-thread flagship and a new motherboard, what does that give you on the gaming front?

This. Our 99th percentile FPS chart provides a geometric mean of the results, converted into an FPS measurement, of all the games in our test suite. That single figure boils the story down pretty nicely, although we've also provided the performance results in each game so you can see how the Core i7-8700K fares in your favorite titles.
Despite a few missteps, the Core i7-8700K lives up to Intel’s claims. Although it doesn't beat the -7700K by a massive margin, the Coffee Lake flagship does deliver better performance in stock and overclocked form. AMD's Ryzen processors still offer competitive pricing and solid gaming performance, but Coffee Lake's gaming performance widens the gap considerably.
Intel's additional cores speed up performance in threaded tasks, which will also be a boon for the streaming crowd, but the faster Turbo Boost (up to 4.7 GHz) maintains the company's advantage in single threaded titles, albeit with a few cases of a slight step back from the Kaby Lake processors.

But bleeding edge performance is only part of the equation. We demand good value--a point AMD drove home with its speedy Ryzen lineup. Intel has obviously taken note, and the additional cores comes without radical price increases. Overall, the Core i7-8700K represents a solid value for those who demand the ultimate in performance, and the lesser Core i5 and i3 SKUs also look promising for the more pragmatic among us.
The Core i7-8700K is simple to overclock and won't require exotic cooling solutions unless you're chasing the bleeding edge, which makes it a fun chip for enthusiasts.
Altogether, the Core i7-8700K is the nimblest gaming chip we've tested, and it also offers surprising performance in our full suite of application tests. As we noted in the review:
Intel has its 10nm Cannon Lake processors coming in the second half of 2018, and AMD has a Ryzen refresh cycle coming next year. Knowing this, should you upgrade now or wait for the next wave of hardware? Due to the iterative nature of most updates, we rarely recommend jumping forward one, or even two generations. However, if you routinely find yourself running productivity workloads that might be served well by Core i7-8700K's extra cores, we could see replacing a quad-core chip with six cores. Gamers interested in maximum performance or streaming also stand to benefit, though in a world of single-GPU graphics configurations, you'd be hard-pressed to bottleneck an overclocked -7700K with even a GeForce GTX 1080 Ti (particularly at the high resolutions it's meant to drive).
The Core i7-8700K took home our Editor's Choice award. So feel free to take a dip in Coffee Lake if you've got the dosh--we doubt you'll be disappointed. We're working on testing the i5 and i3 models now, so stay tuned.

This. Our 99th percentile FPS chart provides a geometric mean of the results, converted into an FPS measurement, of all the games in our test suite. That single figure boils the story down pretty nicely, although we've also provided the performance results in each game so you can see how the Core i7-8700K fares in your favorite titles.
Despite a few missteps, the Core i7-8700K lives up to Intel’s claims. Although it doesn't beat the -7700K by a massive margin, the Coffee Lake flagship does deliver better performance in stock and overclocked form. AMD's Ryzen processors still offer competitive pricing and solid gaming performance, but Coffee Lake's gaming performance widens the gap considerably.
Intel's additional cores speed up performance in threaded tasks, which will also be a boon for the streaming crowd, but the faster Turbo Boost (up to 4.7 GHz) maintains the company's advantage in single threaded titles, albeit with a few cases of a slight step back from the Kaby Lake processors.

But bleeding edge performance is only part of the equation. We demand good value--a point AMD drove home with its speedy Ryzen lineup. Intel has obviously taken note, and the additional cores comes without radical price increases. Overall, the Core i7-8700K represents a solid value for those who demand the ultimate in performance, and the lesser Core i5 and i3 SKUs also look promising for the more pragmatic among us.
The Core i7-8700K is simple to overclock and won't require exotic cooling solutions unless you're chasing the bleeding edge, which makes it a fun chip for enthusiasts.
Altogether, the Core i7-8700K is the nimblest gaming chip we've tested, and it also offers surprising performance in our full suite of application tests. As we noted in the review:
Intel has its 10nm Cannon Lake processors coming in the second half of 2018, and AMD has a Ryzen refresh cycle coming next year. Knowing this, should you upgrade now or wait for the next wave of hardware? Due to the iterative nature of most updates, we rarely recommend jumping forward one, or even two generations. However, if you routinely find yourself running productivity workloads that might be served well by Core i7-8700K's extra cores, we could see replacing a quad-core chip with six cores. Gamers interested in maximum performance or streaming also stand to benefit, though in a world of single-GPU graphics configurations, you'd be hard-pressed to bottleneck an overclocked -7700K with even a GeForce GTX 1080 Ti (particularly at the high resolutions it's meant to drive).
The Core i7-8700K took home our Editor's Choice award. So feel free to take a dip in Coffee Lake if you've got the dosh--we doubt you'll be disappointed. We're working on testing the i5 and i3 models now, so stay tuned.

...residents: the frequency of heavy rainfall events has increased significantly over the past few decades, raising concerns about urban flooding and water management. The study highlights that while light rain remains common, the number of days with intense downpours has risen by nearly 30% since the 1980s. 

This shift in precipitation patterns poses challenges for the city’s infrastructure, which was designed to handle a different climate. Seattle Public Utilities is now focusing on improving drainage systems and enhancing green infrastructure to mitigate flooding risks. 

Experts warn that these changes could lead to more frequent and severe flooding, impacting homes, businesses, and transportation. As climate change continues to influence weather patterns, city planners are urged to adapt and invest in sustainable solutions. Residents are encouraged to stay informed and prepare for the possibility of more intense storms in the future, as the city navigates this evolving climate landscape.

...feeling tired and unrested, with nearly 60% reporting that they struggle to get a full night’s sleep. The study, conducted by the Sleep Foundation, found that factors such as stress, screen time before bed, and irregular sleep schedules are major contributors to this widespread issue. 

Experts recommend establishing a calming bedtime routine, limiting exposure to screens at least an hour before sleep, and creating a comfortable sleep environment to improve sleep quality. Additionally, they emphasize the importance of maintaining a consistent sleep schedule, even on weekends, to help regulate the body’s internal clock.

The consequences of poor sleep extend beyond just feeling groggy; they can include decreased productivity, impaired cognitive function, and even long-term health issues. As awareness grows, many are seeking solutions to prioritize their sleep, recognizing it as a vital component of overall well-being.

Mark Wright has candidly shared his feelings of loneliness while living in Los Angeles, away from his wife, Michelle Keegan. The former TOWIE star revealed that the distance has been challenging, especially as he navigates his busy schedule in the entertainment industry. "I miss her every day," he admitted during a recent interview. "It's tough being apart, but we both understand the importance of our careers."

Michelle, who has been busy with her own projects, recently expressed that while time apart can be beneficial, it also highlights how much they cherish their moments together. "It's nice to spend some time apart to focus on ourselves, but I can't wait to be back with him," she said.

Despite the physical distance, the couple remains committed to their relationship, often sharing sweet messages on social media. Mark emphasized that their love is strong, and they make it a priority to stay connected, no matter the miles between them.

This. Our 99th percentile FPS chart provides a geometric mean of the results, converted into an FPS measurement, of all the games in our test suite. That single figure boils the story down pretty nicely, although we've also provided the performance results in each game so you can see how the Core i7-8700K fares in your favorite titles.
Despite a few missteps, the Core i7-8700K lives up to Intel’s claims. Although it doesn't beat the -7700K by a massive margin, the Coffee Lake flagship does deliver better performance in stock and overclocked form. AMD's Ryzen processors still offer competitive pricing and solid gaming performance, but Coffee Lake's gaming performance widens the gap considerably.
Intel's additional cores speed up performance in threaded tasks, which will also be a boon for the streaming crowd, but the faster Turbo Boost (up to 4.7 GHz) maintains the company's advantage in single threaded titles, albeit with a few cases of a slight step back from the Kaby Lake processors.

But bleeding edge performance is only part of the equation. We demand good value--a point AMD drove home with its speedy Ryzen lineup. Intel has obviously taken note, and the additional cores comes without radical price increases. Overall, the Core i7-8700K represents a solid value for those who demand the ultimate in performance, and the lesser Core i5 and i3 SKUs also look promising for the more pragmatic among us.
The Core i7-8700K is simple to overclock and won't require exotic cooling solutions unless you're chasing the bleeding edge, which makes it a fun chip for enthusiasts.
Altogether, the Core i7-8700K is the nimblest gaming chip we've tested, and it also offers surprising performance in our full suite of application tests. As we noted in the review:
Intel has its 10nm Cannon Lake processors coming in the second half of 2018, and AMD has a Ryzen refresh cycle coming next year. Knowing this, should you upgrade now or wait for the next wave of hardware? Due to the iterative nature of most updates, we rarely recommend jumping forward one, or even two generations. However, if you routinely find yourself running productivity workloads that might be served well by Core i7-8700K's extra cores, we could see replacing a quad-core chip with six cores. Gamers interested in maximum performance or streaming also stand to benefit, though in a world of single-GPU graphics configurations, you'd be hard-pressed to bottleneck an overclocked -7700K with even a GeForce GTX 1080 Ti (particularly at the high resolutions it's meant to drive).
The Core i7-8700K took home our Editor's Choice award. So feel free to take a dip in Coffee Lake if you've got the dosh--we doubt you'll be disappointed. We're working on testing the i5 and i3 models now, so stay tuned.

Intel added two more cores to each of the families and also increased the Turbo Boost frequencies to the highest an Intel chip has seen. Better yet, those increased resources come with a minimal price increase over the Kaby Lake models for the unlocked K-series chips, and the same price for the locked models. We can thank AMD for that.

And No, Coffee Lake will not run in Z270 motherboards.
So, if you whip out your wallet for Intel's six-core, 12-thread flagship and a new motherboard, what does that give you on the gaming front?

The Core i7-8700K took home our Editor's Choice award. So feel free to take a dip in Coffee Lake if you've got the dosh--we doubt you'll be disappointed. We're working on testing the i5 and i3 models now, so stay tuned.

...smoking affects your health should be a wake-up call. Research shows that smoking is linked to a myriad of serious health issues, including heart disease, stroke, and various types of cancer. Beyond the immediate risks, smoking accelerates the aging process, leading to premature wrinkles and a dull complexion. 

Moreover, the harmful chemicals in cigarettes can damage your skin's elasticity, resulting in sagging and a loss of radiance. Quitting smoking can significantly improve your overall appearance and health. Studies indicate that within just a few weeks of quitting, circulation improves, and skin begins to regain its natural glow. 

Additionally, the benefits extend beyond physical appearance; quitting smoking can enhance your sense of taste and smell, improve lung function, and increase your energy levels. If you’re considering making a change, seek support from friends, family, or professional resources. Your future self will thank you for taking the first step towards a healthier, smoke-free life.

...that patients with corneal blindness have access to personalized and readily available transplants. The breakthrough, achieved by a team led by Professor Che Connon, involves using a bio-ink made from human stem cells, which can be printed into the precise shape of a cornea. This innovative approach addresses the global shortage of donor corneas, which affects millions of people worldwide.

The 3D printed corneas were successfully tested in the lab, demonstrating the potential to restore vision. Researchers believe that this technology could be scaled up for clinical use within the next few years, offering hope to those suffering from corneal diseases or injuries. The team is now focused on refining the printing process and conducting further studies to ensure the safety and effectiveness of these artificial corneas in human patients. If successful, this advancement could revolutionize eye care and significantly improve the quality of life for countless individuals.

As usual, we have the deep-dive Coffee Lake coverage in our Core i7-8700K Review: Coffee Lake Brews A Great Gaming CPU review, but for those of you without the time to sift through all 13 pages, we've condensed all of our gaming results to give you a cheat sheet of sorts on Intel's new halo product.
Coffee Lake has arrived, and after nearly a decade of quad-core doldrums in Intel's mainstream desktop space, the company finally decided to bulk up its Core i7, i5, and i3 series. Intel added two more cores to each of the families and also increased the Turbo Boost frequencies to the highest an Intel chip has seen. Better yet, those increased resources come with a minimal price increase over the Kaby Lake models for the unlocked K-series chips, and the same price for the locked models. We can thank AMD for that.
We also have articles that compare Intel's full Coffee Lake lineup to Kaby Lake and a full breakdown of comparisons to AMD's beefy Ryzen stable.
And No, Coffee Lake will not run in Z270 motherboards.
So, if you whip out your wallet for Intel's six-core, 12-thread flagship and a new motherboard, what does that give you on the gaming front?

...Symphony Orchestra will take place at the historic Pallas Theatre in Nicosia. The first concert, scheduled for Thursday evening, will feature a selection of classical masterpieces, including works by Mozart and Debussy, showcasing the rich textures and harmonies that these instruments can create together. 

The second concert, set for Saturday, promises a more contemporary flair, with compositions by modern composers that highlight the versatility of the ensemble. Both performances aim to provide an intimate setting where the audience can experience the nuances of chamber music up close.

Tickets are available online and at the theatre box office, with discounts for students and seniors. Music enthusiasts are encouraged to arrive early to enjoy a pre-concert talk, where musicians will share insights about the pieces being performed. This week’s concerts are not just a celebration of music but also an opportunity to support local talent and the arts community in Cyprus.

...Industrial Average dropping more than 300 points by midday. The S&P 500 and Nasdaq also experienced significant declines, reflecting a broader sell-off across major sectors. Analysts noted that the recent rise in bond yields, driven by expectations of continued interest rate hikes from the Federal Reserve, has raised concerns about borrowing costs and economic growth.

Investors are particularly wary of how a tighter labor market could exacerbate inflationary pressures, leading to a potential slowdown in consumer spending. "The market is reacting to the fear that higher yields will stifle growth," said one market strategist. "With inflation still a concern, any signs of a cooling job market could lead to more volatility."

In response, defensive sectors such as utilities and consumer staples saw slight gains as investors sought safer havens. Meanwhile, tech stocks, which are often more sensitive to interest rate changes, faced the brunt of the sell-off, with many major companies seeing their shares decline sharply.

This. Our 99th percentile FPS chart provides a geometric mean of the results, converted into an FPS measurement, of all the games in our test suite. That single figure boils the story down pretty nicely, although we've also provided the performance results in each game so you can see how the Core i7-8700K fares in your favorite titles.
Despite a few missteps, the Core i7-8700K lives up to Intel’s claims. Although it doesn't beat the -7700K by a massive margin, the Coffee Lake flagship does deliver better performance in stock and overclocked form. AMD's Ryzen processors still offer competitive pricing and solid gaming performance, but Coffee Lake's gaming performance widens the gap considerably.
Intel's additional cores speed up performance in threaded tasks, which will also be a boon for the streaming crowd, but the faster Turbo Boost (up to 4.7 GHz) maintains the company's advantage in single threaded titles, albeit with a few cases of a slight step back from the Kaby Lake processors.

But bleeding edge performance is only part of the equation. We demand good value--a point AMD drove home with its speedy Ryzen lineup. Intel has obviously taken note, and the additional cores comes without radical price increases. Overall, the Core i7-8700K represents a solid value for those who demand the ultimate in performance, and the lesser Core i5 and i3 SKUs also look promising for the more pragmatic among us.
The Core i7-8700K is simple to overclock and won't require exotic cooling solutions unless you're chasing the bleeding edge, which makes it a fun chip for enthusiasts.
Altogether, the Core i7-8700K is the nimblest gaming chip we've tested, and it also offers surprising performance in our full suite of application tests. As we noted in the review:
Intel has its 10nm Cannon Lake processors coming in the second half of 2018, and AMD has a Ryzen refresh cycle coming next year. Knowing this, should you upgrade now or wait for the next wave of hardware? Due to the iterative nature of most updates, we rarely recommend jumping forward one, or even two generations. However, if you routinely find yourself running productivity workloads that might be served well by Core i7-8700K's extra cores, we could see replacing a quad-core chip with six cores. Gamers interested in maximum performance or streaming also stand to benefit, though in a world of single-GPU graphics configurations, you'd be hard-pressed to bottleneck an overclocked -7700K with even a GeForce GTX 1080 Ti (particularly at the high resolutions it's meant to drive).
The Core i7-8700K took home our Editor's Choice award. So feel free to take a dip in Coffee Lake if you've got the dosh--we doubt you'll be disappointed. We're working on testing the i5 and i3 models now, so stay tuned.

As usual, we have the deep-dive Coffee Lake coverage in our Core i7-8700K Review: Coffee Lake Brews A Great Gaming CPU review, but for those of you without the time to sift through all 13 pages, we've condensed all of our gaming results to give you a cheat sheet of sorts on Intel's new halo product.
Coffee Lake has arrived, and after nearly a decade of quad-core doldrums in Intel's mainstream desktop space, the company finally decided to bulk up its Core i7, i5, and i3 series. Intel added two more cores to each of the families and also increased the Turbo Boost frequencies to the highest an Intel chip has seen. Better yet, those increased resources come with a minimal price increase over the Kaby Lake models for the unlocked K-series chips, and the same price for the locked models. We can thank AMD for that.
We also have articles that compare Intel's full Coffee Lake lineup to Kaby Lake and a full breakdown of comparisons to AMD's beefy Ryzen stable.
And No, Coffee Lake will not run in Z270 motherboards.
So, if you whip out your wallet for Intel's six-core, 12-thread flagship and a new motherboard, what does that give you on the gaming front?

This. Our 99th percentile FPS chart provides a geometric mean of the results, converted into an FPS measurement, of all the games in our test suite. That single figure boils the story down pretty nicely, although we've also provided the performance results in each game so you can see how the Core i7-8700K fares in your favorite titles.
Despite a few missteps, the Core i7-8700K lives up to Intel’s claims. Although it doesn't beat the -7700K by a massive margin, the Coffee Lake flagship does deliver better performance in stock and overclocked form. AMD's Ryzen processors still offer competitive pricing and solid gaming performance, but Coffee Lake's gaming performance widens the gap considerably.
Intel's additional cores speed up performance in threaded tasks, which will also be a boon for the streaming crowd, but the faster Turbo Boost (up to 4.7 GHz) maintains the company's advantage in single threaded titles, albeit with a few cases of a slight step back from the Kaby Lake processors.

But bleeding edge performance is only part of the equation. We demand good value--a point AMD drove home with its speedy Ryzen lineup. Intel has obviously taken note, and the additional cores comes without radical price increases. Overall, the Core i7-8700K represents a solid value for those who demand the ultimate in performance, and the lesser Core i5 and i3 SKUs also look promising for the more pragmatic among us.
The Core i7-8700K is simple to overclock and won't require exotic cooling solutions unless you're chasing the bleeding edge, which makes it a fun chip for enthusiasts.
Altogether, the Core i7-8700K is the nimblest gaming chip we've tested, and it also offers surprising performance in our full suite of application tests. As we noted in the review:
Intel has its 10nm Cannon Lake processors coming in the second half of 2018, and AMD has a Ryzen refresh cycle coming next year. Knowing this, should you upgrade now or wait for the next wave of hardware? Due to the iterative nature of most updates, we rarely recommend jumping forward one, or even two generations. However, if you routinely find yourself running productivity workloads that might be served well by Core i7-8700K's extra cores, we could see replacing a quad-core chip with six cores. Gamers interested in maximum performance or streaming also stand to benefit, though in a world of single-GPU graphics configurations, you'd be hard-pressed to bottleneck an overclocked -7700K with even a GeForce GTX 1080 Ti (particularly at the high resolutions it's meant to drive).
The Core i7-8700K took home our Editor's Choice award. So feel free to take a dip in Coffee Lake if you've got the dosh--we doubt you'll be disappointed. We're working on testing the i5 and i3 models now, so stay tuned.

Gamers interested in maximum performance or streaming also stand to benefit, though in a world of single-GPU graphics configurations, you'd be hard-pressed to bottleneck an overclocked -7700K with even a GeForce GTX 1080 Ti (particularly at the high resolutions it's meant to drive).
The Core i7-8700K took home our Editor's Choice award. So feel free to take a dip in Coffee Lake if you've got the dosh--we doubt you'll be disappointed. We're working on testing the i5 and i3 models now, so stay tuned.

...that Ivan Safronov, a prominent journalist and former military officer, was found safe in a nearby town, contradicting earlier reports of his death. Authorities had launched an investigation after receiving alarming information about his alleged murder, which sparked widespread outrage and concern among press freedom advocates. 

Safronov, known for his investigative work on military and defense issues, had been facing legal troubles prior to the incident, including charges of treason that many believe were politically motivated. His sudden reappearance has raised questions about the circumstances surrounding the initial reports of his death and the integrity of the police investigation.

Supporters of Safronov are calling for transparency and accountability, demanding a thorough inquiry into the events leading up to the confusion. The case has drawn international attention, highlighting the risks faced by journalists in Russia, where press freedoms are increasingly under threat. As the story unfolds, many are left wondering what this means for the future of journalism in the country.

the NJAA and the Angus breed. The Angus Ambassador will represent the association at various events, including state fairs, national conventions, and industry conferences, promoting the values and benefits of Angus cattle. Candidates must be NJAA members aged 16 to 21 and demonstrate strong communication skills, leadership qualities, and a passion for the beef industry.

Applications are now open and will be accepted until March 15. Interested individuals are required to submit a written application, a personal statement, and letters of recommendation. Finalists will be interviewed by a panel of judges during the NJAA's annual conference in June.

The selected ambassador will receive a scholarship, travel opportunities, and the chance to network with industry leaders. This role not only enhances the ambassador's personal growth but also helps to elevate the profile of the Angus breed within the agricultural community. For more information, visit the NJAA website or contact the association directly.

and deregulation. Investors were optimistic that Trump's policies would stimulate economic growth and lead to higher corporate profits. The Dow Jones Industrial Average surged, closing up over 250 points on the day following the election, marking one of its largest single-day gains in recent history.

Financial and healthcare stocks led the charge, as traders anticipated significant changes in policy that could benefit these sectors. The prospect of tax cuts was particularly appealing to businesses, which had long been advocating for a reduction in corporate tax rates. Additionally, infrastructure spending plans promised to create jobs and boost demand across various industries.

However, analysts cautioned that the market's enthusiasm could be tempered by the challenges of implementing such sweeping reforms. Uncertainty surrounding trade policies and potential geopolitical tensions also loomed large, prompting some investors to remain cautious despite the initial euphoria. As the transition period unfolded, market participants closely monitored developments in Washington for further direction.
